english:
  title: On the Loyalty and Filial Piety of Zhao Bao
  author: Lee Gok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Can we truly speak of precedence between sovereign and parent? The sages have already addressed this matter. Can loyalty and filial piety truly lack a root and an end? On this I must offer my own perspective.

    Confucius, in expounding the Book of Changes, said: "After heaven and earth exist, then the myriad things exist. After the myriad things exist, then male and female exist. After male and female exist, then father and son exist. After father and son exist, then sovereign and minister exist. After sovereign and minister exist, then superior and inferior exist. After superior and inferior exist, then ritual and righteousness have their proper place." This shows that the relationship between sovereign and parent must have its order. To serve one's sovereign when abroad and one's parents when at home—this is what we practice in our very nature and embody in our persons as we stand between heaven and earth. This is loyalty and filial piety. To remain ignorant of this is to be no better than a beast. Confucius also said: "Through filial piety to parents, one's loyalty can be transferred to one's sovereign." Mencius declared: "There has never been one of humanity who abandons his parents, nor one of righteousness who subordinates his sovereign." Thus loyalty and filial piety are the actualization of humanity and righteousness. Though the duties are twofold, the principle is one. Though our circumstances differ and demand varying degrees of urgency, the root and branch possess a hierarchy that cannot be confused.

    Let me illustrate by recounting the deeds of the ancients. Wu Qi was a capable man of the Warring States period. He abandoned his mother to seek office and killed his wife to gain generalship. His cruelty and base conduct hardly warrant our judgment regarding loyalty and filial piety. Wang Ling was a celebrated minister of the Western Han. When the Hegemon King took his mother hostage to summon him, Wang Ling refused to go. Yet his mother, understanding virtue, took her own life to strengthen his resolve—thus Wang Ling's burden was lightened. This was not confined to scholars and officials. When the High Progenitor contended with Xiang Yu for the world, Xiang Yu placed the Grand Progenitor on a chopping block, threatening to cook him to force surrender. The High Progenitor replied: "I beg you grant me a bowl of the broth." Though this was an unfortunate utterance, one who seeks to rule the world cannot concern himself with family—such reasoning still holds some merit.

    Yet regarding Zhao Bao, who killed both mother and wife to preserve a city entire—the gentlemen commended him and praised his singular virtue. This gives me pause. When Zhao Bao was governing Liaoxis and sent for his mother, the Xianbei invaded, taking his mother and family as hostages. He loaded them upon his chariot to attack the enemy. Weeping, he said to his mother: "Once I was your son, but now I am the minister of my sovereign. Duty forbids me to regard private affection and thereby compromise my loyalty and righteousness." His mother, hearing from afar, replied: "Each person has their fate. How could we regard each other and thus undermine loyalty and righteousness? Press forward." Zhao Bao then advanced and defeated the enemy, yet his mother and wife perished in the struggle. Returning home to bury them, he told the townsfolk: "To draw state salary yet avoid peril is not the act of a loyal minister. To kill one's mother to preserve righteousness is not the act of a filial son." He then coughed up blood and died. This is why the gentlemen honored him—believing he achieved both loyalty and filial piety.

    Their reasoning was this: should Zhao Bao, for the sake of his parents, submit to the enemy and lose his territory and people, he would betray the Han far more greatly. Thus he chose to abandon his mother and family while remaining true to his duty. Having done so, he declared: "I have not betrayed the Han, yet my mother and wife have perished by the enemy's hand, while I alone remain intact to enjoy my reward and glory. This is but selling one's parents for sustenance—how different is it from Wu Qi?" Then he coughed up blood and died. His deliberation in that perilous moment was indeed careful.

    Yet there remains something incomplete in his understanding of precedence and root and branch. His mother did not first resolve herself through righteousness as did Wang Ling's mother, who grasped the sword. When Zhao Bao declared "Duty permits no regard for affection," was this not he who severed the bond first? Were not his mother's words of encouragement spoken from necessity alone? Moreover, victory and defeat cannot be foreseen—how could he guarantee his own survival? By fortune alone he preserved his person, his territory, and his people, yet could not preserve his mother and wife. Thus he too ended his own life. How vastly different is this from Wang Ling, who aided the Han's foundation and brought lasting stability to the Liu house, whose merit was great and whose name was honored?

    Moreover, in the age of Liu and Xiang, victory hung upon a single breath, and the fate of the world and people's welfare rested upon it. Thus the High Progenitor dared abandon his father and wife to pursue his course. Having succeeded, he became Son of Heaven, possessed the four seas, and could use the world to support his parents—what greater filial piety could there be? Yet even here, precedence and root and branch remain incomplete, for his success rested upon fortune alone.

    When one asked Mencius: "If Shun became Son of Heaven and Gao Yao became judge, and the blind old man Gu Sou committed murder, what then?" Mencius replied: "He would be arrested." "But would Shun not prevent this?" "How could Shun prevent it? The law is what was handed down from above." "Then what would Shun do?" Mencius answered: "Shun viewed relinquishing the world as casting away worn sandals. He would secretly carry his father on his back and flee, dwell by the seashore, and spend his life in contentment and joy, forgetting the world entire." Though this is a hypothetical, in dealing with affairs according to principle, one cannot do otherwise. Thus the ancient scholars said: "The words about sharing the broth are intolerable to heaven and earth."

    Zhao Bao was merely a county governor. His domain encompassed but a hundred li and a single county's people. Whether he preserved or lost them mattered little to the Han's fortunes. And at that very time, the sovereign was foolish, ministers corrupt, the loyal and virtuous were destroyed, the people suffered, and teaching had collapsed like a great flood beyond all dikes, or a sickness at the bone beyond all medicine's reach. This was hardly the moment for one eating the sovereign's food and wearing his garments to sacrifice himself for glory.

    Zhao Bao, clinging to petty righteousness, knew only that drawing salary means not avoiding hardship, yet did not understand that aiding the tyrant makes the tyrant prosperous. He knew that killing one's mother to achieve merit was loyalty, yet did not know that preserving oneself to serve parents is filial piety. He vainly admired Wang Ling's virtue but in truth obtained only Wu Qi's cruelty. In a time when action was impossible, he performed what need not be performed. Thus we say: "Zhao Bao's loyalty and filial piety were incomplete."

    What then should Zhao Bao have done? I say: Had he applied Mencius's principle of secretly carrying his father on his back and dwelling in contentment by the sea, the public and private would have been clearly distinguished. Had he applied Confucius's teaching to appear when the Way prevails and to remain hidden when it does not, he would have avoided sudden calamity. The matter of Zhao Bao concerns the teachings of our Way and must be carefully examined. Thus this discourse.
